TY  - JOUR
T1  - Real Options as Engines of Choice and Heterogeneity
AU  - McGrath, Rita Gunther
AU  - Ferrier, Walter J.
AU  - Mendelow, Aubrey L.
Y1  - 2004/01/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2004.11851720
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2004.11851720
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 86
EP  - 101
VL  - 29
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Four characterizations of options exist: (1) as a component of total firm value, (2) as specific projects, (3) as choices, and (4) as a heuristic for strategic investment. Option value exists when two conditions apply: future choices and potential for proprietary access to outcomes. Narrower boundary conditions are inconsistent with theory and incomplete for application. The option lens has promise for its power to shed economic insight into behavioral processes.
AB  - Four characterizations of options exist: (1) as a component of total firm value, (2) as specific projects, (3) as choices, and (4) as a heuristic for strategic investment. Option value exists when two conditions apply: future choices and potential for proprietary access to outcomes. Narrower boundary conditions are inconsistent with theory and incomplete for application. The option lens has promise for its power to shed economic insight into behavioral processes.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2004.11851720
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2004.11851720
Y2  - 2026/04/24
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Real Options and Real Tradeoffs
AU  - Adner, Ron
AU  - Levinthal, Daniel A.
Y1  - 2004/01/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2004.11851738
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2004.11851738
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 120
EP  - 126
VL  - 29
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The commentaries on our article fail to come to grips with the distinct challenges raised by a process of experimentation that leads to the discovery of new possible initiatives. These challenges differ from those posed by an investment that provides privileged access to a prespecified set of possible follow-on investments. By treating these challenges as simple problems of implementation, the commentaries ignore the strategic tradeoffs implied by efficient abandonment processes and, therefore, fail to clarify where the logic of real options is likely to be more (and less) helpful to strategy thinking.
AB  - The commentaries on our article fail to come to grips with the distinct challenges raised by a process of experimentation that leads to the discovery of new possible initiatives. These challenges differ from those posed by an investment that provides privileged access to a prespecified set of possible follow-on investments. By treating these challenges as simple problems of implementation, the commentaries ignore the strategic tradeoffs implied by efficient abandonment processes and, therefore, fail to clarify where the logic of real options is likely to be more (and less) helpful to strategy thinking.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2004.11851738
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2004.11851738
Y2  - 2026/04/24
